{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_irving_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280659782/1927081201/0607.xml":{"full_text":"2\nSUMMER SCHOOLS\nGRADUATION HELD\nSeventy-Nine Pupils Pro\nmoted \u201445 Others Re\nceive Diplomas.\nGraduation exercises are being held\ntoday for 79 SB pupils who, through\nattendance at the Summer schools\nhave earned the privilege of entering\nhigh school next month. Exercises also\nare being held at the Dunbar High\nSchool for 45 pupils who have qualified\nthrough attendance at the Dunbar Va\ncation High School to receive the\nusual graduation diploma.\nToday marks the close of the most\nsuccessful Summer school session ever\nheld, according to Assistant Supt.\nof Schools Walter B. Patterson, di lec\ntor of special activities. Mr. Patterson\ndeclares that tiie pupils in attendance\nat tlie Summer schools eagerly have\ntaken advantage of their opportunity i\nto \"make up\" work with the result j\nthat a high percentage will be pro-j\nmuted when school, reopens next Sep- j\ntember.\nThe graduation of 73 SB pupils who j\nwill go to high school next month took J\nplace at Central High School this j\nmorning while the graduation of the j\n45 pupils who are receiving the regu-\nlar high school diploma was held at\nDunbar High School at. 11:30 o'clock.;\nWhile the older pupils were holding\ntheir graduations, the pupils in the\nSummer elementary schools were en- j\njoying programs of entertainment and\nexhibitions of handwork.\nList of Graduate*.\nNames of the SB pupils graduated\nfit Central High School today follow:\nClass instructed by C. K. Barnard\nTo Business High School: Thomas\nGarrison. John Higgins, Fiorello Od\ndone ami Annie Schmidt. To Central\nHigh School: Richard Elgin. Freder\nick Halt, Nathan Marks, Mark Ra\ncioppi and Constance Orphanos. To\nEastern High School: Christine Al\ndrich and Frances Wahler. To Mc-\nKinley Technical High School: Pan!\nHawkins and Wilton Smith. To\nWestern High School: Andrew Conlyn j\nend George Kowzee.\nClass instructed by W. NT. Costigan:\nTo Business High School\u2014-Emma\nHahn, Marjorie McKinley, Louise D.\nOsterwald. Helen R. Stone and Matil\nda R. Wood; to Central High School\u2014\nHarry Fowler, Barbara M. Griesbauer, i\nCatherine Kline. Edith R; Parker and\nClara Sohneiberg: to Eastern High\nSchool\u2014Lloyd L. Bramble. Charles K.\nlew. William A. McClosky, Edward\nE. O'Brien, Franklin J. Richards, Ste\nphen 1 Smith, Ainsworth Tucker.\nKenneth Wade. Lester Wade, Ida V.\nLyons. Mary L. Snouffer, Ruby L.\nWhitley and Ethel M. Jost; to McKin\nley Technical High School\u2014Hugh B.\nChapman. Fred E. Kennard. Olin Mc-\nKnight, George F. Sesso. Marguerite\nDoffer and Rynell B. Stork: to West\nern High School \u2014Reed M. Farvell,\nNadine Brownfield. Eleanor Coffey.\nEmeline Jennings, Margaret Kline and\nWinifred Kohler.\nClass instructed by C. L. Stack:\nTo Business High School\u2014Rita Am\nbrogi, Mary Beck, Madaline Cambrey\nand Ruth Crump.\nTo Central High School\u2014Charles\nBlackburn. Richard Bodmer, Mar\ngaret Ballden. Lillian Berman, Lo\nraine Bold, Helen Dettweiler. Mar\ngaret Laws and Florence O'Dono\nghue.\nTo Eastern High School\u2014Marshall\nBaker, Douglass Collins. David Har\ndester, Marvin Lohr, Blanche Leh\nman. Louise Sellner and Virginia\nThomas.\nTo McKinley Technical High School\n\u2014Kenneth Larigey, V\nTo Western High Sdhool\u2014John Har\ndester, Campbell Pryor and Martha\nSherier.\nJohn F. Cook Vacation School:\nTo Dunbar High School Donald\nBernard Hill and Eleise Velma Mur\nray.\nTo Armstrong Manual Training\nFrhool\u2014Elroy Cartwright Lewis. John\nRufus Roberts, Anna Louise Bowser\nand Corrine Green.\nPupils who received high school\ndiplomas at Dunbar High School fol\nlow:\nArmstrong Technical High School:\nAlonzo James Aden, Horace Lucius\nRobinson and Carrie Elizabeth Love.'\nDunbar High School, academic de\npartment: William Calvin Curtis.\nClyde C. Freeman, William Ennis\nHenry, Fitzgerald Huntington Jenkins,\nRichard Henry Gaskins, jr.; Curley\nKing, Lewis Addison Morse, Frank\nLeslie Norris, Ned Riston J\u2019erry, Al\nfred Vergil Pettie. William Edmon\nRav, jr.; Silas Franklin Shelton. Wil\nliam Elmer Toyer, Charles Ann Myles,\nGertrude Edmonia. Anthony, Beulah\nEugenia Barber, Alice Genevieve\nBetz, Elleene Magdalence E. Brown.\nAlice Butler. Nellie Beatrice Cheat\nham, Dorothy Viola Carter, Vera\nBernice Cooper, Annie Elizabeth\nHairston, Florence Beverly Howell.\nLeona Eleanor Jackson. Mabel Cecelia\nLancaster, Eunice Genevieve Moss,\nCarmel Priscilla Neale, Althenia Eliza\nbeth Queen, Evelyn Leaner Smith.\nMarvis Alexandra Taylor, Lucy Ljiza\nbeth Turner, Gladys Evangeline ll\nliams. Paulina Manila Washington\nand Helen Virginia Williams.\nDepartment of business practice,\nfour-year course: Homer Franklin,\nBeulah Eugenia Barber and Edna\nFreeman Guy.\nShaw Junior High: George Thomas\nJones, Mattie Barnes. Evelyn ashti\nLane, Gladys Alberta Powell and\nEvelyn Alma Harley.\nGrade School Programs.\nDean D. O. W. Holmes of Howard\nTTniversitv made the address to\ngraduates at Dunbar High school\nwhile Asst. Supt. of Schoole Lugen..\nA dark awarded the diplomas.\n\u2018\u2018Grandma\u2019; Spelling Lesson, ft\ndramatization, was given by the sixth\ngrade publis at the S. J. Brown \\aca\ntion School today. Pupils who took\npart in the program at this school\nincluded: Jennie Werber. Lva Katz.\nMona Wilson. Percy Keyser. Michael\nlnfshitz, Ruth Selsky. Gertrude\nRubenstein. Katie Coppos. Lena\nKaufman. Clarence Browning, Tejeda\nDekelbaum, Ruth Katz and Marie j\nGsell.\nA doll contest ?*mi a ball srnme\ntured the program at the Force\nSchool. Poems were recited by Edith\nFitch, Jeanette Phillips, Virginia\nCoulter and Edith Kind.\nAt the E. V. Brown School a num\nber of piano and violin solos were\nnn the entertainment program. Pupils\nparticipating included: Tracy Mulli\ngan, Christine Merritt. Ann Bono,\nMary Ann Mulligan, John Tucker,\nj tr-P-'n Fails, Mary Voigt and Esther\nConner.\nA program of 27 numbers was given\nat the Bryan School, with the follow\ning pupils taking part:\nFrances Acton, Helen Flournoy,\nDorothy Hargett, Caroline Johansen,\nThomas Cooper, Muriel Anderson,\nHelen Weiskey, Archie Griest, Althea\nMcNabe, Mary Peluzzo, Dorothy Darl\ning, Mary Cupp. Louise Acton, Ralph\nWeed, Rosemary O\u2019Lone, Marian\nDiven. Gladys Powell, Laura Binkley,\nFrances O\u2019Lone. Anna Babbie, Irma\nSmith, Mae Gillard, Earl Burgess,\nEdwin Green, George Ely, Edith\nAsher, Daniel Gevlnson, Thelma. A fi\nsher, Bernice Clear, Catherine Brad\nley, Clara Harper, Louise Crooks,\nJane Cohort, Catherine Butler, Freda\nRicketts. Abraham Widone. Lillian\nJones, Elaine Reich, Robert De More\nland, Edward Mc\u00dfady, Marie Nostadt.\nElise Thompson, Margaret Thompson,\nEleanor Neely, Doris Rohrliac.h. Janet\nRock, Anna Sakolsky and Mary Ellen\nBailey.\nDaily w\u00bbather observations are\nmade at about 5.000 places in the\nUnited States and its possession*, n _\nWins Promotion\n\nllir fB i\nJm f Am\nNELSON T. JOHNSON. _\n18 ARE ARRESTED\nIN MIDNIGHT RAID\nThree Accused of Violating\ni i\nDry Law at House on\nCanal Road.\nA midnight raid last night at 5201 j\nCanal road, near Chain Bridge, re- j\nsuited in the arrest of IS men and\nwomen, who were charged with dis\norderly conduct, while three persons\nwere charged with violations of the j\nprohibition laws.\nThomas Burton Reid, 26 years old, j\nand his brother Joseph, 24 years old,\nwere charged with sale and posses\nsion of intoxicants. Their sister,\nClara Hart. 23 years old, was charged\nwith illegal possession. The men j\nwere released on bond in the sum of\nSI,OOO and the girl furnished a SSOO\nbond for her appearance.\nTwo in Army Uniforms,\nTwo of those arrested for disorderly\nconduct were in Army uniform and\ngave the names of William Thomas\nMeade, 32 years old, Bushkill, Pa.,\nand Harold Martin, SO years old. 1221\nReservoir street. They- stated that\nthey had been directed to the premises\nby a stranger.\nThe raiding party reported the\nseizure of 1.000 bottles of home brew\nand several bottles of liquor. The raid j\nwas based on a previous visit, of plain j\nclothes men, it was stated, who j\nclaimed that they purchased honv\nbrew for 25 cents a bottle and liquor i\nfor $2 a pint.\nFour Patrol* Required.\nThe raiders, who occupied three au- 1\ntomobiles in a quick sortie on the j\nbuilding, W'ore headed by Capt. Wil- j\nliam G. Stott and Lieut. McGill Grove I\nof the fourteenth precinct. It took\nfour police patrols to carry the pris\noners to the fourteenth precinct sta\ntion house.\nIn Police Court today the Reids de\nmanded jury trial. Joseph was held on\n$l,lOO bond and Thomas, SI,OOO.\nCharges against Mrs. Hart were\nnolle pressed. Other defendants j\ncharged with disorderly conduct for- j\nfeited $5 collateral by not appearing\nin court.\nEarly yesterday afternoon police of i\nthe thirteenth precinct# commanded j\nby Capt. Lord, anti accompanied by\nrevenue agents, raided 5103 Georgia\navenue, arresting Clarence Edwin\nHepner, 22 years old, and confiscat\ning 1,245 bottles of alleged home brew\nbesides a distilling outfit. Hepner\nwas charged with manufacturing and\nillegal possession of intoxicants and\nwas released on SSOO bonds.\nPoliee stated that a man and Wom\nan disappeared through a back dom\nes they came in the front. The raid\nwas made after citizens had reported\nthat 40 or 50 persons were seen en\ntering and leaving the house.\nHUNGRY BURGLARS\nROB SAFE, THEN EAT\nMarket Loses S2OO Cash After\nBandits Enjoy Lunch Be\nhind Counter.\nBurglars entered the Old Dutch i\nMarket, 310\" M street, last night and\nate 4ome bologna and blew a safe.\nHidden behind a pile of sugar sacks,\nthey cracked the safe, tearing the\ndoor from its hinges, and stole ap\nproximately S2OO. An inch piece of\nbroken hit. used in boring a hole\nthrough which to pour the explosive,\nwas found near the wrecked safe.\nEvidently' working leisurely, the\nburglars partook of a light lunch back\nof the counter, drinking four bottles\nof milk and eating a piece of bologna.\nEntrance to the store was gained by\nforcing a basement door and then\nprying open a double-locked door lead\ning to the main floor. It was the same\nmethod used in the robbery last Mon\nday morning of the Old Dutch Market\nit 811 Fourteenth street, and, like that\nmarket, the establishment robbed last\nnight has a record of robberies. Last\nFail the safe was rifled, the burglars\nleaving it in the icebox. Both rob\nberies were discovered by the man\nager, C. E. Harper.\nFIREMEN IMPERILED\ni BY STREAM FROM HOSE\nH. J. Bicksler of Loral Engine\nCompany, Knocked Into River,\nNarrowly Escapes Injuries.\nI Thrown into the water by the force\n|of tiie hose on the Firefighter while\nbattling a blaze at Twelfth and \"Water\nstreets southwest late yesterday\nj afternoon. H. J. Bicksler, 24 years\nI old, member of No. 16 Engine Com\npany, narrowly escaped injury from\nI i he propeller of thy tire boat before be\nling assisted to shore by Private\nj George W, Rock of No. .13 Engine\nI Company, who plunged overboard to\nthe rescue of bis companion.\nThe powerful stream of water sent\nout by the flreboat also inflicted\nslight injuries on C. W. Reid of No.\n16 Engine Company and Caesar Young,\ncolored, of No. 4 Engine Company. The\nflreboat and the engine companies had\nresponded to an alarm from the lum\nl,er yard of Johnson 'Wimsatt,\n1 Inc. The fire was extinguished quick\n|v and damage was estimated at S2OO.\nReports for Temporary Duty.\nMaJ. Martin F. Scanlon, Army Air\nCorps, formerly in command of Boll\ning Field, Anacostia, and for the past\nthree years assistant military attache\nat the United States embassy, Rome,\nItaly, lias reported to the War De\npartment for temporary duty in thA\ngeneral staff corps, preparatory to\ntaking a course of instruction at the\nAir Corps Tactical School at Langley\nField, Va., beginning -n**t months\nTHE EVEYIITO STAff, WASHIYfoTOY. T>. T\u201e EffTTHT. 'ATYtrST 1?. 1027,'\nNELSON T. JOHNSON\nGETS HIGHER POST\nDivision Chief Promoted by\nPresident to Be Assistant\nSecretary of State.\nNelson T. Johnson, chief of the Far\nI Eastern Division of the State Depart\nI ment and a recognized authority on\n(Chinese affairs, yesterday was ap\ni pointed Assistant Secretary of State.\nI The appointment was made by the\nI President and announced from the\nSummer White House. Mr. Johnson\nwill succeed to the post vacated by\nthe promotion of Robert E. Olds to\nthe undersecrrtarysliip of the depart\nj ment in succession to Joseph C. Grew,\nj new Ambassador to Turkey.\nThe new Assistant Secretary, a na\ntive of the District of Columbia, has\nbeen in tiie department sinee 1907.\nwhen In' entered as a student inter\npreter in China, lie passed through\nall grades in the consular service and\nafter a series of assignments in China\nwas ordered back here for specialized\nwork.\nBecomes Expert Assistant.\nlie was deiailed as an expert as\nsistant on Far Eastern questions dur\nj ing the conference on limitations of\n[armaments here in 1921 and in 1924\nbecame a foreign service officer and\nassistant to the then chief of tlie Far\nEastern Division, John Van A. Mac-\nMurray, w ho subsequently was named\n[.Minister to China.\nJohnson has been chief adviser to\n[Secretary Kellogg on the Chinese prob\nlems of the last two years, and in that\ncapacity has frequently had occasion\ntn confer with President Coolidge on\ndevelopments of the Chinese situation.\nAs an Assistant Secretary he will eon\n[linue to exercise general supervision\nover departmental activities in connec\ntion with policies in the Far East.\nHe is a graduate of George Wash\nington University.\nOther Changes in Service.\nI Other changes in the foreign service\nI announced at the State Department\ninclude the following: Frederic R. Dol\nbeare of New York, counselor of le\ngation, from Bern to Ottawa! Ilallett\nJohnson of New Jersey, first secre\ntary, from Paris to Oslo; David McK.\nKey of Tennessee, from consul at Ant\nwerp to third secretary at Berlin; John\nH. MaeYeagh of New York, second\nsecretary, from Managua to Washing\nton. It. C.: John I*. Moffatt of New\nYork, first secretary, from Ottawa, to\nWashington, D. C.; Edward L. Reed\nof Pennsylvania, first secretary, from\nBerlin to Brussels: Clifford \\V. Me-\nGlasson of the District of Columbia,\nvice consul, from Prague to Port Said;\nMaxwell I#. Hamilton of lowa, consul,\nfrom Shanghai to Washington. D. C.;\nSamuel W. Honaker of Texas, consul,\nfrom litis city to Port au Prince; Rob\nert D. Longyear of Massachusetts,\nconsul, from Geneva to this city.\nFred C. East in. jr., of Missouri, con\nsul at Sno Paulo, has resigned.\nAID ASKED IN HUNT\nFOR ELMER R. BAYNE\nPolice of Capital and Maryland\nUrged to Search for Missing\nYouth.\nPolice authorities of Washington\nand Maryland were asked today to\nsearch for Elmer R. Bayne, 22 years\nold. of 29 Grant place, who disap\npeared Wednesday, leaving behind\ntwo farewell notes to friends.\nOne note, addressed \u201cMarjorie\u201d\nand written in pencil on a small piece\nof paper, was found Tuesday pinned\nto Bayne's automobile, which had\nbeen parked in front of a home at\nClinton, Md. The note bade Marjorie\n\u201cgood-by, forever,\u201d and was signed\n\u201cElmer Another note said, \u201cGood\nby. Roderick and Buddy, Elmer.\u201d\nBayne has not been seen since\nhe got oil of Buddy Middleton's auto\nmobile within 100 yards of his par\nents\u2019 home, at Clinton, last Wednes\nday night, saying lie was going to\nvisit his father and mother, Mr. and\nMrs. R H. Bayne. The note was\nfound Tuesday, but as Bayne was\nseen the next evening at Clinton,\nlittle attention was paid to it. Tiie\nother note was found in Bayne's room,\non Grant place.\nWhen last seen Bayne was wear\ning a blue serge suit, black patent\nleather shoes and a Panama hat,\nwith brown hand. He is of tall,\nslender build and weighs about 130\nor 135 pounds. His parents say he\nwas extremely mild-mannered and of\ntemperate habits.\nWORLD DROPS WORK\nOF HEYWOOD BROUN\nArticles Discontinued Because of\n\u201cExtravagant Opinions\u201d on\nSacco-Vanzetti Case.\nBy the Assoeiated Pick*.\nNEW YORK, August 12.\u2014Ralph\nPulitzer, editor of Ihe New- York\nWorld, in a signed statement in that\npaper today announced that articles\nbv Hey wood Broun, one of the stand\ning features, had been discontinued\nbecause Broun insisted upon discuss\ning the Sacco-Vanzetti case \u201cafter two\narticles in which lie had expressed his,\npersonal opinion with utmost extrava\ngance.\u201d\nThe last Broun article, published\nAugust 6, contained the following\nparagraph:\n\u201cFrom now on, I want to know,\nwill the institution of learning at Cam\nbridge, which once we railed Harvard,\nI lie know n as Hangman's House?\u201d\nPickets before the Starehouse in\nBoston Wednesday carried placards\nwith another quotation from a pre\nvious article which asserted \"If all the\nvenerable college presidents in ihc\ncountry tottered forward and pro\nnounced the men guilty, they would\nstill lie innocent.\"\n\u201cTiie World has always believed in\ntallowing the fullest possible expres\nsion of individual opinion to those of\nits special w riters who w rite under\ntheir own names.\" said Mr. Pulit\nzer\u2019s statement. \u201cStraining its inter\npretation of ihis privilege, the World\nallowed Mr. Broun to write two arti\ncles on the Sacco-Vmizetti case, in\nwhich lie expressed his personal opin\nion with tiie utmost extravagance.\n\u201cThe World then instructed him, now\nthat he had made his own position\nclear, to select other subjects for ids\nnext articles. Mr. Broun, however,\ncontinued to write on the Sacco-Van\nzetti case. The World, therefore, ex-\nI ercising its right to final decision as to\nj what it will publish in its columns,\nhas omitted afl articles submitted by\nBroun.\nBroun told the Associated Press he\nj would devote his time to the writing\nnf magazine articles, or perhaps would\nreturn to Hie stage.\nRuth Hale, president of the Lucy\nStone League and Broun\u2019s wife, was\none of tiie New Yorkers to go to\nPoston to picket th\" statehouse.\nGets Radio Parley Berth.\nLeighton TV. Rogers of the Depart\nment of Commerce ha* been appoint\ned assistant secretary of the Ameri\ni<an delegation, \u00abf the International\n1 Radio Telegraph Conference. The ap\npointment *vae announced today,\n\u201cKING\u201d BEN ADMITS HE LACKS\nDIVORCE FROM HIS FIRST WIFE\nCult Leader, on Stretcher in\nCourt, Defends House of\nDavid Colony.\nDenies Charges Made\nAgainst Him by Women.\nTells of Life.\nBy the Associated Press.\nST. JOSEPH. Mich.. August 12.\n\u201cKing\u201d Benjamin Purnell, on the stand\nas a witness for himself in the State's\ndissolution suit against tin* House of\nDavid, today admitted on cross-exami\nnation by Assistant Attorney George\nI-!. Nichols that he had never secured\na legal divorce fro mliis first wife.\n\"Eighteen or nineteen attorneys told\nitu* 1 didn't need one. I was only an\nignorant boy then,\u201d tie said.\nIt lias been the contention of tiie\nStates that Purnell was a bigamist.\nHis wife, \u201cQueen\u201d Mary, had previous\nly Insisted that Purnell bad secured a\ndivorced and that she was legally mar\nried to Purnell.\nThe admission came after a. com\nparatively brief direct examination by\nPurnell's own counsel in which, in a\nmonotone of \u201cnoos\u201d and \u201cI never did,\u201d\nBenjamin categorically denied charge\nafter charge that lias been laid against\nhim by State witnesses.\nTestified Front Cot.\nPurnell was brought into court on\na stretcher and permitted to testify\nfrom the cot. Tiie courtroom was\ncrowded and back of Benjamin were\nscores of his followers. A colony nurse\nhovered attentively around the cult\nleader\u2019s stretcher.\nPurnell said lie was born March 27.\n1861. Jle was somewhat vague con\ncerning his early life, but said that\nlie and Mary Purnell, who testified\nyesterday, had been members of a\ncolony headed by Michael Mills, in\nDetroit, some 20 years ago,\n\u201cI don\u2019t think 1 did,\u201d was his an\nswer to a question as to whether he\nhad written two pamphlets introduced\nhv tiie State and claimed to instruct\ncolony members to perjure themselves\nif necessary.\nHe denied flatly any mistreatment\nof girl or woman members of the col\nony and also denied ever having of\nfered \u201chush money\u201d to Ruth Swan\nson. a State witness, to persuade her\nnot to testify about mistreatments al\nleged by the State.\nPurnell told his cross examiner that\nbe married Angeline Brown in Green\nup County, Ky., when he was 16\nyears old.\nPLANE CARRIERS\nNEAR COMPLETION\nLast of New Cruisers Will Be\nFinished by 1930. Navy\nResume Indicates.\nBy the Associated Pres*.\nA resume of work on ships now\nunder construction by the Navy show\ned that the aircraft carriers, Lexing-\nton and Saratoga, both will he com-\nplejed .by next January 5, and all of\nthe last three of the eight 10,000-ton\ncruisers authorized by Congress by\nMarch 13. 1930.\nIt showed also that all of the six\nriver gunboats being constructed for\nHie Navy by tlt a K >ngn;tn Dock\nEngineering Works in China, which\nhave been held up by labor troubles,\nwill lie finished by January 1\u00ab> next,\nand that by September 1. .1929, the\nthree fleet submarines. V-4, V-5, and\nV-6, will be added to the naval lists.\nThe carrier Lexington, previously\nestimated for completion on Novem\nber 27. was 93.2 per cent complete on\nAugust 1. It will be ready by January\n5, while the Saratoga. 96.5 per cent\ncomplete August 1, is scheduled for\ncompletion October 31.\nThe fight cruisers Pensacola and\nSalt Lake City are due to he complet\ned July 9, 1929. On August 1 the\nPensacola, being built at the New\nYork Navy Yard, was 13.7 per cent\ncompleted, while the Salt. Lake City,\nunder rontruetion by the American\nBrown Boveri Electrical Corporation,\nwas 20.3 per cent on the way. Less\nlhan 1 per cent, of the preliminary\nwork on the other six cruisers had\nbeen started on August 1.\nCLUE TO ACID BOMB\nTOSSER THOUGHT FOUND\nMrs. Brooke\u2019s Information May Aid\nPolice in Locating\nAssailant.\nAlthough still confined to her home,\n1736 North Capitol street, from shock\nand pain induced by an acid bomb\nthrown through a street, ear window\nagainst, her right arm Monday night.\nMrs. Cora Lee Brooke stated this\nmorning that she believed that she\nhad obtained a clue as to her mys\nterious assailant and will actively as\nsist police in their investigation.\nMrs. Brooke has held several eon\nferences- with detectives nf the fifth\nprecinct, who are investigating the\nbomb throwing, and expressed the\nhope today that the mystery will Vie\ncleared up shortly. She stated that\nher arm appeared to lie better yester\nday but that the small sear where she\nwas seared by the acid began to burn\nagain this morning and she appeared\nto have lost her strength in that\narm.\nAwarded Scholarship.\nMildred Stohlman, daughter of Wil\nliam Stohlman. Somerset, Md., an\nalumnus of Immaculata Seminary,\nhas won a scholarship to the College\nof St. Ma ry-of-the-Woods. Indiana,\nawarded by Mrs. Crnigie Gunn\nMitchell, president, of its alumnae, for\nstraight A grades during the entire\nhigh school course.\nIn announcing the winning of tiie\nscholarship by Miss Stohlman officials\nj of Immaculata stated that she was\npresident and honor pupil of her class\nand president of tiie athletic associa\ntion.\nDog Days End After Flouting Tradition\nBy Bringing Subnormal Temperatures\n\u201cDog days\u201d departed yesterday, con\nsiderably chastened by the coo! recep\ntion they received this year.\nHeralded as the hottest period of tiie\nyear, when men suffer and dogs go\nmad. dog days this season fell down\non tradition and supplied Washington\nwith temperatures pleasantly subnor\nmal, according to records of tiie\nWeather Bureau.\nDog days are supposed to begin\nJuly 3 and end August 11. and they\nget. their name from tiie Slimmer an\ntics of Sirius, the dog star. Sirius, it\nseems, selects this period to join with\nOld Sol in his morning rising habits,\nand the conjunction of the two usually\ncoincides with sultry weather.\ni:l VI \\\\!l\\ n I; M I I\nHe described what lie termed tiie\n\u201clighting of tiie graph.\u201d lie explain\ned there was a spirit of truth taking\nits place in him. it happened. Vie said,\nwhile be was a pillar of the Michael\nMills Colony, and led him to break\naway from Mills\u2019 faith and set himself\nup as the \u201cseventh messenger.\u201d At\nthe time Mills was serving a jail sen\ntence on charges of abusing girl\nmembers of bis colony.\nPurnell said lie broke away from\nMills: because \u201cMichael never had any\nfait h.\u201d\nAfter nn hour and 35 minutes of\ntestifying, counsel for Benjamin in\nsisted the cult leader was exhausted.\nHe was wheeled back to his ambu\nlance and returned to the colony, it\nwas reported he would lie returned to\nthe courtroom for completion of cross\nexamination as soon as lie is able,\nprobably this afternoon or tomorrow\nmorning.\nPurnell looked weak. His eyes\nflashed and his gestures were ani\nmated, however. He wore a cap\npulled far down over his long gray\nha ir.\nPurnell\u2019s voice was so weak that\nthe stenographer was forced to repeat\n.his answers for the benefit of the\ncourt. Vie rested his head on the rot\npillow as though he were tired. De\nfense counsel asserted \u201che is a very\nsick man and will not he kept on the\nwitness stand for long periods at a\ntime.\u201d\nPurnell replied with quavering neg\natives when asked if lie had set up\n\u201can inner circle of Shiloh Girls\u201d or\nhad posed as \u201cGod Emmanuel, tiie\nPrince of Peace or Gabriel.\u201d\nBenjamin insisted there were no\ntunnels nr hiding places in Shiloh or\nany other House of David buildings.\n17,MATI LIGHT\nTO BE TURNED ON\nLamp to Be Exhibited Tues\nday Will Blister Skin at\n1,000 Feet.\nBy th<* Associated Prr<\u00ab*.\nNEW YORK, August 17. A light'\nso strong that it will produce the ef\nfect of sunburn at a distance of two\nmiles, and will blister the skin of a\nperson standing 1,000 feet away will\nbe turned on at 8 o\u2019clock next Tues\nday night at Charlottesville. Va.. the\nGeneral Engineering Management Cor\nporation announced yesterday.\nThe searchlight will have a beam of\n1,385,000,000 candlepower, which will\nlie visible 200 miles. The crater arc of\ntiie light, it was announced, will be\nthe hottest spot, on earth when J 7.200\nwatts are turned on to give the light\nits full power. The temperature of\nthe crater will be approximately 38.000\ndegrees Fahrenheit and the crater will\nbe \"as bright as the sun at high\nnoon.\u201d\nThe light, said to Vie five times more\npowerful than any used heretofore,\nwill Vie exhibited under full power in\nconjunction with the Institute of\nPublic Affairs now in session at. the\nUniversity of Virginia. The Virginia\nPublic Service Co. will sponsor the\nexhibit.\n\u201cIf the \"Wilson observatory were on\nMars,\u201d an engineer of the corporation\nsaid, \u201cit. will be possible for one there\nto tell tlie minute and hour the light\nflashed on at Charlottesville.\u201d He\ndescribed the huge beam ns com\nparable to a streamer of flaming gas.\nIt was expected that when the light\nshall he swung around in a circle, it\nwill be visible at all first-class Amer\nican observatories.\nLEE BOULEVARdTaRK\nOPENING TOMORROW\nWashingtonians Invited to Attend\nCeremonies at Woodland Site,\nNear Ballston.\nResidents of Washington and near\nby Virginia have been invited to join\nin a field day tomorrow south of Balls\nton. Va.. in celebration of the opening\nof a new 43-acre woodland park along\nthe proposed Lee boulevard, it was\nannounced today by Dr, S. M. .John\nson, president of the National Boule\nvard Association.\nAddresses will Vie made by Rev. Dr.\nPerry I#. Mitchell, pastor of tiie Clar\nendon Baptist Church; C. It. Ahalt,\npresident of tiie Arlington County\nChamber of Commerce; M. E. Church,\nArlington County civic leader, and Dr.\nJohnson.\nThe exercises, to begin at 3 o\u2019clock,\nwill include a ball game between Ar\nlington and Fairfax County teams, an\nold-fashioned basket dinner and the\nspeeches.\nThe gathering is part of a \u201cget\ntogether\u201d movement for tiie Virginia\nregional area. Dr. Johnson states. The\nimmediate objective is united support\nof the program to widen and straight\nen Lee Highway from Falls Church to\nKey Bridge and to build the Lee bou\nlevard and a direct road leading to it\nat tiie Fort Myer reservation from\nKalis Church, Ballston and Clarendon,\nhe explains.\nGovernment, weather officials put no\nfaith in Sirius as a weather prophet,\nand they pointed out today that their\nforecasts recently would have fallen\nwide of the mark if they had depend\ned on tradition. July, it was said, had\nan average temperature of 76 degrees,\nwhich is slightly below normal,.while\n9 nf the first 12 days of August have\nbeen two or three degrees below\nnormal.\nMeanwhile, the stay-at-home vaca\ntionists are congratulating themselves\non the foresight in saving the ex\npense of an out-of-town trip by bask\ning In the Capital\u2019s balmy climate this\nSummer,\nTAX CUT UNLIKELY,\nDAVIS DECLARES\nSecretary Warns Farmers\nNecessities Demand\nLarge Funds.\nBy the Associated Press.\nMOOSE HEART, August 12.\u2014Secre\ntary of Labor James .1. Davis, speak\nins yesterday to 30,000 farmers of\nIllinois attending the annual picnic\nhere of the Illinois Agricultural As\nsociation, declared that money cannot\nbo appropriated by the Government\nfor many important necessities if\ntaxes are reduced.\n\u201cThere is great agitation because\nof the surplus of $(135,000,000.\" said\nSecretary Davis. \"In face of this\nthere is t.'llk of farm relief, for which\nthe minimum amount needed will he\n*300,000,000. The flood relief fund for\nthe Mississippi valley, together with\nthe Boulder Dam revelopment, will\nrequire millions, and millions more\nwill he needed to connect the oceans\nwith the fireat Rakes. It is all right\nto talk about reduced taxes, but not\nin view of such a program.\n\u2018\u2018People should remember the old\nsong entitled. \u2018Eggs Without Darn\nAre Not Worth a Damn,\u2019 and if those\nwho direct the expenditures of the\nGovernment do not have the money\ncoming in to pay for these develop\nments and if you reduce taxes first,\nit will he pitiful for the party in\npower. They cannot raise taxes\nonce they have been reduced.\"\nSecretary Davis spoke briefly on the\nsubject of selective immigration. He\nsaid he favors an amendment to the\nlaw, to provide for uniting families\nwho are on both sides of the ocean.\nLabor is the \"only great subdivision\nof human endeavor\" that is acting\nfairly toward the farmer, said Senator\nKenneth McKellar (Democrat) of Ten\nnessee, who praised the McNary-Hau\ngen farm relief bill.\n\u201cMore than thirty millions of our\npeople are engaged in agriculture\u2014it\nis a basic industry,\" .Senator McKellar\nadded. \u201cThe average income for the\naverage farmer is $730 a year. All\nother groups average $1,415 a year.\nThese figures tell their own story of\nspecial benefits to all groups except\nthe farmers.\"\n\"I am on my vacation, and am re\nsponding to an invitation made to me\nin St. Paul by the President to visit\nturn at the Summer White House,\"\nSecretary Davis said. He denied that\nhe had been summoned to Rapid City\nby the President.\n\u201cConditions throughout the country\nare fine, and they are going to get\nbetter,\" the Secretary declared. He\nseemed much impressd with South\nDakota crop conditions, observed in\nbis flight over the eastern part of the\nState. After his visit with the Presi\ndent, the Secretary expects to return\nby rail to Huron, where he will re\nenter the airplane for a flight to Wash\nington.\nPRESIDENT OF TYPOS\nIS VICTOR IN CLASH\nHoward Faction Wins in Contest\nOver Pensions and Mailers\u2019\nUnion Issues.\nBy the Associated Pres*.\nINDIANAPOLIS, August 72.\u2014The\nfifth day of the six-day diamond jubi\nlee convention of the International\nTypographical Union opened here to\nday with file two biggest, issues before\nthe delegates settled and with the\nprogressives, headed by Charles P.\nHoward, president, victorious in each\ninstance.\nA rule fixing the retirement age in\ntlie old-age pension laws at 60 years\nafter 25 years of continuous working\nmembership was adopted. A proposal\nput forward by the Mailers\u2019 Union\nasking permission to withdraw its\nmembership from the Typographical\nin ion and asking the appointment of\na committee to determine the property\nrights of the mailers in the interna\ntional was voted down, 296 to 201.\nThe administration faction which\nhas control of the executive council\nand which Is headed by James M.\nL,\\ neb, defeated for re-election as\npresident in 1926 by Howard, vigor\nously contested the progressives in i\nargument on the two issues before\nvotes on them were taken.\n'1 he desire of the mailers to with\ndraw from the International follow\ncharges by them that they are being\ndiscriminated against by the printers.\nI hey claim some of the amendments\nintroduced Ijave sought (o remove the\nmailers representative from the execu\ntivc council and to limit their voting\npower. j\nresident Howard announced that t\nv\\ Ilham Green, president of the Amer-\n\u2022can federation of Labor, will address i\nthe convention this afternoon,\ntheater men indorse\n50-CENT TICKET PROFIT\nNew York Houses Favor \"Mc\u00dfride\nPlan\" Requiring SIOOOO\nBond for Agencies.\nB.v the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, August 12.\u2014-Theater\nowners, representing 75 per cent of j\nAew York\u2019s playhouses, last night i\na proved the \"Mc\u00dfride plan,\u201d which!\nprovides for the sale, of tickets by\nagencies at not more than 50 cents\nover boxoffice prices.\nfifty-six theaters, including the\nFlorenz ZJegfeld interests, were rep\nresented at the meeting. Among the\nleading owners not represented were\ntile Dillingham and Krlunger houses.\nTheater owners said that whiie\nagencies other than that of William\nMc\u00dfride, a leading ticket agency\nowner, who suggested the plan, bad\nnot approved the plan, they expected\nno difficulty on that point.\nThe i>lan would require ticket,\nbrokers to post SIO,OOO bonds to guar\nantee performance of their obligations\nand its operation would lie controlled\nby an arbitration board of five.\nJUSTICE McCOY WARNS\nOF RADICALISM MENACE!\nIn Luncheon Address Stresses i\nNeed of Educating Aliens in\nTJ. S. Customs and Traditions.\nThe importance of educating aliens\nas to the customs and traditions of\nthis country as a means of keeping\nthem from becoming radicals was\nstressed by Chief Justice Walter I.\nMcCoy of the District Supreme Court\nin an address at a luncheon of the\nCosmopolitan Club in the Lee House\nyesterday.\nJustice McCoy declared that every\neffort should be made \u201cto catch the\naliens as they come in,\" in order that\nthat, they might he taught the Ameri\ncan Ideals of patriotism and Justice,\nlie praised the local Americanization\nSchool and declared that only about\none of a thousand graduates of such\nschools is likely to become a radical.\nHe also emphasized the deep interest\nshown by the students in such schools,\nadding that they often know more\nabout the United States Constitution\nthan native-born Americans.\nFrederick J. Rice, president of the\nclub, presided at the luncheon.\nStill Holds Reins\nIdifll\u00dfki\nJHKi l\u00bb|lj\n111 l\nI VHpV v jH\nPRESIDENT (OSGRAVK.\nMEXICAN LAND LAW\nAPPEALS POSSIBLE\nProf. Shepherd Says Interna\ntional Statutes Insure\nProtection.\nBy the Associated Pres*.\nWILLIAMSTOWN, Mass., August\n]2.---American nationals in complying\nwith Mexican property laws, as\nevolved under the \u201cC\u2019alvo principle,\"\ndo not necessarily renounce diplomatic\nprotection by the I'nited States, said\nProf, \\V. R. Shepherd of Columbia\nUniversity at the round-table discus\nsion of the Institute of Politics today.\nRecourse may be taken to interna\ntional law, which protects citizens\nabroad, he said.\nAnother phase of the Mexican prob\nlem discussed by Prof. Shepherd was\nj the apparently retroactive effect that\nhe declared Mexico\u2019s alien land law\ni will have. This statute he termed\nretroactive, \u201cif not also confiscatory in\nspirit and tenor.\u201d\nDiscussion of international debt set\ntlements brought forth opposition\nfrom the West and agreement front\nthe Hast. George Winfield Scott, for\nmer Columbia University professor of\ninternational law, contended that the\nlevies had been laid on a sound legal\nbasis of capacity to pay, while Henry\nA. Wallace of Des Moines, son of a\nformer Secretary of Agriculture, as\nserted that the debt burden eventually\nresolved upon the American farmer\nthrough reduction of European buying\npower.\nFelix Morley of the editorial staff\nof the Baltimore Sun in his address\ncriticized American ignorance of Ori\nental history, politics and philosophy\nas a cause of Chinese hostility toward\nAmericans.\nR. E. CLAUGHTON RITES.\nServices Held This Afternoon, Rev.\nW. A. Eisenberger Officiating.\nFuneral services for Richard E.\nCiaughton, 61 years old, vice president\nof the Washington Stock Exchange,\nwho died in Garfield Hospital Wed\nnesday afternoon, were conducted at\nthe residence of his sister-in-law, Mrs.\nJohn M. Beavers, 1752 Columbia road,\nI this afternoon at 2 o'clock. Rev. Wil\nliam A. Kisenberger. assistant pastor\nof the Church of the Covenant, offl\nj <dated. Interment was in Rock Creek\nCemetery,\nPallbearers were C. C*. Glover, presi\ndent of the Washington Stock Ex\nchange; David N. Rust, Uawrence\nSlaughter. J. Morris Woodward,\nCharles Stott and Charles Sifford.\nCONSIDER FASTER BUSSES\nEstablishment of express service on\nits motor bus lines running from Pet\nworth to Eighth and Pennsylvania\navenue and to Potomac Park Is being\ngiven some consideration jjy the\nWashington Rapid Transit Co. If the\ncompany decides to seek approval for\nsuch service it may ask that the ex\npress busses come downtown .on some\nstreet other than Sixteenth, iit order\nto avoid congestion on that thorough\nfare in rush hours.\nThe company also is considering\nother changes in schedules to improve j\nservice after the 31 new busses jus\nauthorized are received.\nCOOLIDGE MAY RUN~\nIF HE IS DRAFTED,\nPARTY MEN ASSERT\nV\n(Continued from First Page.)\nthe opposition party, that his re-elec\ntion was a foregone conclusion.\nSecretary Davis is discussing a va\nriety of subjects relating to the I,a\nhor Department with the President to\nday. He brought with him some fig\nures showing a slight increase in un\nemployment. He explained, however,\nthat this unemployment is only in\nspots. He said he expects an im\nprovement when Fall sets in. >*(t\\\nmentioned tlie textile, steel, window\nglass and cherry-growing industries\nas being the principal ones where\nthere is unemployment.\nThere is a slight business recession\ngenerally, according to Mr. Davis\u2019 ob\nservations. but he feels satisfied that\nthe situation will grow no worse and\nthat within a few months there will\nhe a noticeable improvement. He said\nthe slump in. the industries where\nthere is a letting down in employment\nis due to a large extent to foreign\ncompetition. This competition could\nhe met without any difficulty if the\ntariff on the articles in question was\nincreased, he said.\nSecretary Davis reported to the Pres\nident that the bituminous coal strike\nis dragging along with no prospect\nof an immediate settlement. He said\nthat the general competitive fields are\nthe only ones affected. He said there\nare 50,000,000 tons of soft coal in\nstock and that there is no reason to\nhe alarmed about any shortage.\nMr. Davis said the matter of the\nFederal Government deporting Sacco\nand Vanzeiti, as has been suggested,\nhas never been put to him.\nEugene Mever. jr., head of the re\norganized Federal Farm Loan Board,\nanother visitor expected today, is\nunderstood to have been summoned\nby tlie* President for the purpose of\ndiscussing the agricultural situation\nand to pass judgment upon ideas pre\nsented to him this Summer looking\nto extending relief to the farmers.\nBrig. Gen. Herbert M. Lord, di\nrector of the budget, will arrive at\nthe game lodge tonight loaded down 1\nwith figures relating to preliminary\nestimates of the Government depart\nments. He and the President will\ngo over these estimates .tonight and\ntomorrow to determine w hat shall be\nallowed In the preparation of the i\nbudget.\nALLEGED RUM SHIP\u2019\nCUTS BARGE IN TWO\nj 34 Men Arrested, 7 Trucks\ni and 3 Cars Captured, With\n$500,000 Cargo.\nBy the Associated Prc...\nj NEW YORK. August 12. The .vjh\naotiia, a single-stacker steamboat, s Jd\nby police to contain a half million-deb\nlar load of contraband liquor, was aji\nchored under guard off the Statue bf\nLiberty today after it had fled frntn\nj tack of almost haif a hundred Staten\nthe surprise attack of almost half a\nhundred Staten Island police, had cut\na sand barge in two in the Kill Yon\nI Kull and had run upon a sand bar.\n'where it was captured by the (\u2019mu\niuard.\nThirty-four men were arrested by\nthe Staten island police, who also cap.\nj lured seven 7-ton trucks and three \u00bbj,-\npensive automobiles. It) addition. the\nCoast Guard made prisoners of 36\nmen aboard the Ansonia.\nSecond in 24 Hours.\nThe steamer was the second alleged\nrum runner to he captured in New\nYork Harbor within 24 hours. The\nBritish steamer Sebastopol was taken\nyesterday with a load of liqtior esti\nmated hy the Coast Guard to he worth\n$300,000 at bootleg prices, and the\ncrew of 17 men was held for hearing\nlatPfl. Thp stapo] was also t\u00ab rh*\nnically classified as a pirate ship be\nmuse it was said to have change\u00ab| jf*\nname at sea to the Westmoreland.\nPatrolman Dauria early today saw\nthe single stacker tied up at an\nabandoned dock at. Arlington with\nabout one hundred men gathered\naround a fleet of waiting trucks ap-\npatently preparing to unload the\nsteamer's cargo.\nHh telephoned for reinforcements\nand when these arrived and called\nupon the throng to surrender th\nwas a wild scramble to escape.\nThirty-four men, however, including\nthose police believe to he the ring\nleaders, were arrested.\nPuts Barge in Two.\nWhile the police were busy taking\ntheir prisoners the crew of the steam\ner, which had not yet begun to un\nload, cut the boat loose from the\ndock and started at full speed\nthrough the waters of the Kill Vori\nKull. In his haste to escape the\nhelmsman ran his boat into two\nanchored sand barges, cutting one\nof them cleanly in two and causing\ntwo men on board to he thrown head\nlong into the water.\nThe alleged rum runner careened\nonward through the darkness until\nit ran its prow- high and dry onto\na sand bar.\nPolice said that all the men cap\ntured except six were truckmen and\nlaborers. The six occupied expen\nsive automobiles which w-ere lined\nup on the pier with the trucks.\nThe Ansonia was described as a lake\nsteamer. The only American freighter\nAnsonia listed bv the Bureau of Navi\ngation was built in Cleveland eigh*\nyears ago and was formerly called the\nLake Forney. The Ansonia Steam\nship Corporation of Wilmington was\nlisted as the owner. Before arriving\nhere she was last mentioned as arriv\ning at Norfolk, Va.\nWOODLOTHIANCLUB\nWILL TAKE CRUISE\n\nI Department Store Employes\u2019 Group\nto Leave Tonight for Two-\nDay Outing.\nThe Woodlothian Club, composed of\nI employes of Woodward Lotlnop de\npartment store, will embark tonight\non a two-day cruise aboard the S.\nj Southland to Old Point Comfort. Nnr\nfolk. Hampton Roads and Yorktown,\nreturnirfg early Monday morning.\nI Reaving the employes\u2019 entrant eof\nthe-store at 6:3\u00ab o'clock tonight, the\nI club members will he conveyed to the\nj Seventh street wharf in busses, where\nthey will he photographed prior to\nthe departure of the steamer,\nscheduled for 7:30. A program of\ndancing, from 8:30 until midnight, hns\nbeen arranged, with a \"gold pti;;e\u201d\nwaltz at 10:30 p.m.\nThe boat will arrive in Norfolk at\n6 o'clock tomorrow evening and will\nleave at midnight to anchor in Hamp\nton Roads. Early Sunday morning\nthe party will arrive at Old Point Com\nfort and after religious services and an\ninspection of Fort Mon roe the boat\nwill leave for Yorktown.\nPoints of interest about Yorktown\nwill be visited and at s:3'* p.m. the\nboat will begin Its journey homeward. A\nAt 8:30 Sunday evening the Wood\nlothian Chorus will present a. sacred\ncantata. Music for dancing and din\nj ner will be furnished by the Wood\nlothian orchestra.\nFollowing is the Woodlothian cruise\ncommittee: General chairman. Gees*\nH. Davis; secretary, Miss Marion B.\nSnyder. Committee on arrangements:\nGeorge D. Halsey, Harry Mockhe*.\nTicket committee: Miss Louisa Wie\ninan. chairman; Miss Cora\u201d Cud worth.\nPublicity committee: J. W. itardv,\nchairman; Richard Harvey. Enter\ntainment committee: B. P. Wheatley,\nchairman: H. G. Lees, Miss E. Duck,\nL. S. McCarthy, L. K. Ashford. Com\nmittee on dancing: J. Hall, chairman;\nC. A. Riden. Committee on conces\nsions: JL L. Richardson, chairman.\nReligious services: Stanley Robinson.\nConcert hy the chorus: \\y. H. Star\nhell, chairman.\nLEWIS W. OLDHAM DIES.\nWar Department Messenger Served\nfor 20 Years.\nLewis W. Oldham. 43 years old. r O I- 1\nored, who had served as a messenger\nand clerk in the War Department for\nmore than 20 years, died at his r--si\ndence, 1320 T street, yesterday after\na long illness.\nwas a member of Social Lodge.\nNo. 1. F. A. A, M., colored, and Rising\nSun Lodge. No. 1365. G. I*. O. O. F.\nHe also belonged to the Florida Ave\nnue Baptist Church, anti hid been ac\ntive in Boy Scout activities, serving\nas- scoutmaster of Troop 505. He was\nonce in the second-hand furniture\nbusiness.\nHe is survived hy his widow, Mrs.\nAlma Gandy Oldham: three brothers.\nJohn W\u201e Rev. P. B. and Rev. G W.\nOldham, and a sister, Mrs. Rena Hen\nderson.\nBAND CONCERT.\nBy the United States Army Band,\nat the Tuberculosis Hospital. Four\nteenth and Upshur streets, at 7:3d\no'clock tonight.\nProgram.\nMarch, \u201cAmerica First\u201d Losev-\nOver tu re to \u201d11 Ouarany\" Gomez\nMexican waltz. \u201cPesos y Pesos,\"\nMartinez\nTwo popular songs\u2014\n(a) \u201cRosy Cheeks\"., Simmons\n(b) \u201cMe anil My Shadow\"... .Jolson\nSelections from \u201cThe Sunshine\nGirl\" Rubens\nCharacteristic piece, \u201cOn Tiptoe.\"\nHosmer\nAir de ballet, \u201cPolka Caprice\u201d.-Perlet\nNovelty, \u201cMaryland\u201d Short\n(With solo variations for different\ninstruments.)\nMarch, \u201cSagamore\" Goldman\n\u201cThe Star Spangled Banner.\u201d","height":"27138","width":"20565"}}
